<p>
<p>Calculate the Pearson correlation coefficient, if given</p>
<ul>
<li>Mean of X: 0.5</li>
<li>Average of Y: 0.5</li>
<li>Standard deviation of X: 0.2</li>
<li>Standard deviation of Y: 0.25</li>
<li>Covariance between X and Y: 0.039</li>
</ul>
</p>]]></text>
</questiontext>
<generalfeedback format="html">
<text><![CDATA[<p>
<p>To calculate the Pearson correlation coefficient, we need not only the means and standard deviations of the two variables, but also the covariance between them. Here is the formula we will use:</p>
<p><span class="math inline">\(r = \frac{\text{cov}(X, Y)}{\sigma_X \sigma_Y}\)</span></p>
<p>in which:
- <span class="math inline">\(r\)</span> the Pearson correlation coefficient is.
- <span class="math inline">\(\text{cov}(X, Y)\)</span> the covariance between <span class="math inline">\(X\)</span> and <span class="math inline">\(Y\)</span> is.
- <span class="math display">\[sigma_X$ is the standard deviation of $X$ is.
- \]</span>sigma_Y$ the standard deviation of <span class="math inline">\(Y\)</span> is.</p>
</p>]]></text>
</generalfeedback>
